text: List is a collection which is ordered and changeable. Allows duplicate members. Tuple is a collection which is ordered and unchangeable. No duplicate members.

text: I'd just like to update that now there's a simpler way to get the same result as union, intersection and difference have. So let's say we have 2 sets: a and b. Instead of a.union(b) now you can just type a | b.  a & b for intersection.  a - b for difference (just remember that a - b ‚â† b - a) also a ^ b for symmetric difference (it'll only get the items that don't repeat themselves in both sets) Hope it helps :)

author: @markkennedy9767
text: At 10:00 where you showed that the .pop method actually returns something (the item you removed), this is another example of what seem to me the idiosyncrasies that arise in Python. What I mean is that even though we are dealing with a mutable object (a list), courses.pop returns something and courses itself is changed as it is a list (a mutable object). Compare this with courses.remove which returns nothing and again courses is changed as it is a list (object).    Compare this again with methods acting on a string e.g. courses , an immutable object where now, say courses.replace would return a value and courses would not be modified. There's no real consistency: I would have thought mutability/immutability correlated with a method not returning/returning a value. Until .pop messes this up by being halfway between the two: It both modifies in place (mutability) AND returns a value for courses.pop. Python is definitely more elegant than most languages but it seems at times like it's thrown together. Admittedly I am a relative beginner, so I may be missing a deeper meaning to the apparent inconsistency above.

author: @thecowmilk4857
text: @CoreySchafer, I know that this is too late to write but you forgot to explain to beginners how to access list inside a list indexes.  To access the indexes of a list inside a list we can use 'double square brackets "[ ][ ]" ' to the first list. Writing: courses  = ['History', 'Math', 'Physics', 'CompSci'] courses2 = ['Art', 'Education']  courses.insert(0, courses2) print(courses[0][0])  This will print the index 0(which in original list is another list) and the index 0 of the list inside which is 'Art'  Note: the second square bracket always refers to the second list(if there is any in the specified index in the first square bracket), if the specified index is not a list but a word then it will access the first letter on that word. Second example:  courses  = ['History', 'Math', 'Physics', 'CompSci'] courses2 = ['Art', 'Education']  courses.append(courses2) print(courses[0][0])  Will print out 'H' because: the 0 index is the word "History" and this word is spliced into: ['H', 'i', 's', 't', 'o', 'r', 'y']

author: @carolchang619
text: The simulated clock example brings up a few points about nested loops: An inner loop goes through all of its iterations for every single iteration of an outer loop. Inner loops complete their iterations faster than outer loops. To get the total number of iterations of a nested loop, multiply the number of iterations of all the loops. 255 Program 4-17 shows another example. It is a program that a teacher might use to get the average of each student‚Äôs test scores. The statement in line 5 asks the user for the number of students, and the statement in line 8 asks the user for the number of test scores per student. The for loop that begins in line 11 iterates once for each student. The nested inner loop, in lines 17 through 21, iterates once for each test score

text: Anyone who want almost all the code he wrote :   #Lists courses = ['history','math','physics','CompSci']  #length of the list print( len( courses))  courses[0] courses[3] courses[-1]  courses[0:2] courses[:2]  #insert and append courses.append('art') courses.insert(0,'art') print(courses)  courses = ['history','math','physics','CompSci'] courses_2=['art' ,'Education']  courses.insert(0,courses_2) print(courses)  #extend courses.extend(courses_2) print(courses)  #remove popped = courses.pop() #pop returns/outputs the removed/popped vairable   courses.reverse() ; print(courses)  courses.sort() ;  print(courses)  courses.sort(reverse=True) ;  print(courses)     #without changing the original list sorted_courses = sorted(courses) ; print (sorted_courses)   nums=[1,3,4,2,5] min(nums) max(nums) sum(nums)  print(courses) courses.index('math')   #for   for item in courses:     print(item)  for index, item in enumerate(courses):     print(index, item)           #to start at different index for index, item in enumerate(courses, start=1):     print(index, item)   #convert lists to strings courses = ['history','math','physics','CompSci']  courses_str='- '.join(courses) ; print(courses_str)   #convert strings to lists new_list=courses_str.split('- ') ; print(new_list)   #tuples #immutable as in not changable   # Mutable list_1 = ['History', 'Math', 'Physics', 'CompSci'] list_2 = list_1  print(list_1) print(list_2)  list_1[0] = 'Art'  print(list_1) print(list_2)   # Immutable  tuple_1 = ('History', 'Math', 'Physics', 'CompSci')  tuple_2 = tuple_1   print(tuple_1)  print(tuple_2)   tuple_1[0] = 'Art'  # print(tuple_1) # print(tuple_2)  # Sets  #no order is retained cs_courses = {'History', 'Math', 'Physics', 'CompSci'};print(cs_courses)    #duplicated values are removed cs_courses = {'History', 'Math', 'Physics', 'CompSci','Math'} ;print(cs_courses)   #whether a value is a part of a test #sets does it more efficiently and optimized to find this print('Math' in cs_courses)   art_courses={'History', 'Math', 'Art', 'Design'}   print(cs_courses.intersection(art_courses)) print(cs_courses.difference(art_courses)) print(cs_courses.union(art_courses))   # Empty Lists empty_list = [] empty_list = list()  # Empty Tuples empty_tuple = () empty_tuple = tuple()  # Empty Sets empty_set = {} # This isn't right! author: @bozkurtkaankaraoglan1420
text: Thank you for the excellent course. As I watch and learn I also play with the examples you give.  I noticed I can use min() and max() methods with string literals in a list.  courses = ["history", "math", "physics", "art", "education", "compsci"] print (min(courses)) will return Art because the string starts with A and conversely the Max() method for the same list will return Physics because P is the closest letter to Z.   Another note: with pop() method I can use index numbers for the items. If there are 4 items I can use pop(1), pop(2), all the way to pop(3) because the index starts with zero. Pop() allows negative numbers too. pop(-1) will pop the very last item, pop(-2) next to the last item etc...

author: @jamesblock8384
text: The only thing I would maybe still mention is the ability to do something like list_2 = list_1,copy() as an option. That way you get all the methods of a list and ability to alter list_2 without affecting list_1. Similar to how you would use the spread ( ... ) operator in javascript. Just keep in mind there's pros and cons to doing this. Mainly, that list_1 is still mutable and maybe you'd like it to be immutable.  You can also typecast between list, sets, tuples using the respective methods list(some_iterable) tuples(some_iterable) and set(some_iterable). I know the video was getting kinda long but I think this rounds out the video a little more. Cheers, thanks for the tutorials.

author: @ShynggysZ
text: cheat sheet: courses = ['History', 'Math', 'Physics', 'CompSci'] len(courses) courses[-1] accessing last item of list by index courses[0:2] from 0 index up to but not including 2 courses[:2] or courses[2:] courses.append('Art') courses.insert(0, 'Art') insert at index courses.insert(0, courses_2) inserts whole LIST AS ONE ITEM into a list using index courses.extend(courses_2) joins two lists by each individual items in a lists courses.remove('Math') courses.pop() removes and returns removed value courses.reverse() reverses in place courses.sort(reverse=True) sorts in descending sorted_courses = sorted(courses) for sorting not in place min(num), max(num), sum(num) courses.index('CompSci') shows the index of item 'Art' in courses shows True or False, contains or not for index, course in enumerate(courses, start = 1): loops through each item in courses using index that starts with 1 course_str = ' -  '.join(courses) converts a list into a string using separator new_list = course_str.split(' - ') converts a string into a list using separator  mutable vs immutable tupples are immutable sets doesn't have order and duplicates cs_courses.intersection(art_courses) shows items in common in both sets cs_courses.difference(art_courses) shows items that are in cs_courses but not in art_courses cs_courses.union(art_courses) all courses in two sets empty_set = set() use this form to create empty set, empty_set  = {} creates an empty dictionary
